My work focuses on interpretable machine learning, which is crucial for responsible and trustworthy AI. My goals are
to: (1) design interpretable machine learning methods that are as accurate as black box methods, including sparse decision
trees, scoring systems and interpretable neural networks, (2) apply interpretable machine learning to important societal
problems, focusing on healthcare, criminal justice, and scientiﬁc discovery, (3) provide a theoretical foundation for why
interpretable-yet-accurate models exist for a vast set of problems in supervised learning, (4) assist with regulation of AI,
and (5) provide educational tools on interpretable machine learning (via online course materials).
I am the winner of the 2022 Squirrel AI Award for Artiﬁcial Intelligence for the Beneﬁt of Humanity from the Asso-
ciation for the Advancement of Artiﬁcial Intelligence (AAAI) Similar only to world-renowned recognitions, it carried a
monetary reward at the million-dollar level. I am the recipient of the 2025 John McCarthy award from the International
Joint Conference on Artiﬁcial Intelligence (IJCAI), the 2024 INFORMS Society on Data Mining Prize, and a 2022 Guggen-
heim fellowship. My team won 2nd in the prestigious 2023 Bell Labs Prize. I won the INFORMS Innovative Applications
in Analytics Award three times (2013, 2016, 2019) based on applied work with domain experts. Some accomplishments:
• The Rashomon Set paradigm: My team introduced a new paradigm for interpretable machine learning – instead of the
algorithm providing one model (as usual), we return all low-error models, allowing the user to choose between them.
This eliminates the interaction bottleneck to users. It allows fairness and monotonicity constraints to be handled
instantly – by taking a simple loop over the models and ﬁltering out models that do not obey the constraints. We are
developing this for sparse decision trees, sparse generalized additive models (GAMs), and scoring systems.
• Why interpretable models are accurate: My collaborators and I established a mathematical framework for why interpretable
models are as accurate as deep learning or other black box models for most tabular data sets.
• Risk scores: Our algorithms for sparse risk scores were applied to important healthcare and criminal justice applications:
our risk score for seizure prediction in ICU patients allows for better allocation of patient monitoring resources. This
work won the 2019 INFORMS Innovative Applications in Analytics Award. It helps to prevent severe brain damage
in critically ill patients, and is the only AI model widely used in critical care brain monitoring (the 2HELPS2B score).
• Breast cancer prediction: Our AsymMirai algorithm is the ﬁrst accurate, interpretable model that predicts breast cancer up
to 5 years in advance. We found subtle asymmetries that radiologists did not know about previously.
• Dimension reduction for data visualization: The useful and award-winning PaCMAP algorithm was designed by my lab.
We used it to discover clusters of people with HIV that seem to have different types of immune system characteristics.
• I work heavily on AI regulation. I am on the National AI Advisory Committee’s Subcommittee on Law Enforcement. I
was on the National Academies Committee on Facial Recognition Technology that released a 2024 report.
• Energy reliability: I led the ﬁrst major effort to maintain an underground electrical distribution network using ML, in work
with Con Edison in NYC. This won the 2013 INFORMS Innovative Applications in Analytics Award.
• Crime series analysis: My collaborators and I developed code for detecting crime series in cities. Our Series Finder
algorithm was adapted by the NYPD into their Patternizr algorithm, which has been running live in NYC since 2016
for determining whether each new crime is related to past crimes.
• I have served or chaired important committees for INFORMS, the American Statistical Association, AAAI, SIGKDD,
DARPA, and the National Academy of Science, Engineering and Medicine. I participated in the U.S. Senate AI
Insight Forum on transparency, explainability, intellectual property and copyright.
• I have given invited/keynote/plenary talks at INFORMS, KDD (2014 & 2019), IJCAI, AISTATS, ECML-PKDD, ML in
Healthcare, FAT-ML (Fairness, Accountability, and Transparency), SIAM International Conference on Data Mining
(SDM), and the Nobel Conference. My work appears in the NY Times, Washington Post, Boston Globe, Wall Street
Journal, MSNBC, Fox, National Public Radio, STAT, the Times of London, Businessweek, and the News & Observer.
• I am writing an e-book on introductory machine learning called “Intuition for the Algorithms of Machine Learning,” which
teaches interpretable machine learning as part of the basic ML curriculum, linked on my website.
• Margins for AdaBoost: I solved a well-known (previously open) theoretical problem in machine learning as a PhD student,
which is whether AdaBoost maximizes the ℓ1- margin. Subsequent work solved a COLT open problem.

